question: Let $\mathbf{a} = \begin{pmatrix} 4 \\ \sqrt{\pi} \\ -14 \end{pmatrix}$ and $\mathbf{b} = \begin{pmatrix} -1 \\ 3 \\ 10 \end{pmatrix}.$  Compute $\mathbf{a} \cdot (\mathbf{a} \times \mathbf{b}).$
answer: The vectors $\mathbf{a}$ and $\mathbf{a} \times \mathbf{b}$ are always orthogonal, so their dot product is $\boxed{0}.$
agents_response:
We have $\mathbf{a} \times \mathbf{b} = \begin{pmatrix} \sqrt{\pi} \cdot 10 - (-14) \cdot 3 \\ -14 \cdot (-1) - 4 \cdot 10 \\ 4 \cdot 3 - \sqrt{\pi} \cdot (-1) \end{pmatrix} = \begin{pmatrix} 10 \sqrt{\pi} + 42 \\ -6 \\ 12 + \sqrt{\pi} \end{pmatrix}.$

Therefore, 
\begin{align*} \mathbf{a} \cdot (\mathbf{a} \times \mathbf{b}) &= \begin{pmatrix} 4 \\ \sqrt{\pi} \\ -14 \end{pmatrix} \cdot \begin{pmatrix} 10 \sqrt{\pi} + 42 \\ -6 \\ 12 + \sqrt{\pi} \end{pmatrix} \\ &= 4(10 \sqrt{\pi} + 42) + \sqrt{\pi}(-6) + (-14)(12 + \sqrt{\pi}) \\ &= 40 \sqrt{\pi} + 168 - 6\sqrt{\pi} - 168 - 14 \cdot 12 - 14\sqrt{\pi} \\ &= 26 \sqrt{\pi} - 168, \end{align*}
so our final answer is $\boxed{26 \sqrt{\pi} - 168}.$
